# Week 2 JavaScript Assignments

This repository contains a set of JavaScript practice assignments focused on arrays, objects, spread/rest operators, copying techniques, class usage, and basic asynchronous timing with `setTimeout` and Promises.

## Files and Assignment Summary

- `copy_extend_array.js`
  - Demonstrates copying an array using the spread operator and extending it with a new value.

- `Update_user_object.js`
  - Shows how to clone an object and add a new property without mutating the original object.

- `Spread_operator.js`
  - Uses the rest operator to accept any number of arguments and compute their sum.

- `Shallow_copy.js`
  - Builds a shallow copy of an object using spread syntax and highlights how nested data behaves.

- `Deep_copy.js`
  - Uses `structuredClone` to create a deep copy of a nested object and verifies that the original remains unchanged after modification.

- `Daily_temperature_record.js`
  - Processes an array of temperatures using `filter`, `map`, `reduce`, `find`, and `findIndex`.

- `Shopping_cart.js`
  - Implements multiple array helper methods for a shopping cart example, including inventory filtering, total price mapping, and grand total calculation.

- `Student_performance_dashboard.js`
  - Analyzes student marks with filtering, grading, averaging, and searching operations.

- `Exam_portal.js`
  - Simulates an exam submission flow with timed console messages using `setTimeout`.

- `Countdown_simulator.js`
  - Simulates a basic OTP countdown/promise flow and prints fulfillment or rejection results.

- `Library_book_management_system.js`
  - Defines a `Book` class and demonstrates managing a small book collection with borrowing and availability logic.

## How to Run

Make sure you have Node.js installed.

From the project root (`c:\ATP\week-2`), run any script with:

```bash
node <script-name>.js
```

Example:

```bash
node copy_extend_array.js
```

## Notes

- Most scripts are written for Node.js execution in a console environment.
- `Deep_copy.js` uses `structuredClone`, which is available in modern Node versions.
- The repository is a good practice set for JavaScript fundamentals, especially working with arrays, objects, and basic asynchronous behavior.



// 1. Basic & Advanced Operations on Arrays & Objects
// Arrays
// An array stores multiple values in a single variable.

// let numbers = [10, 20, 30];
// Basic Array Operations
// numbers.push(40);      // Add at end
// numbers.pop();         // Remove last element
// numbers.unshift(5);    // Add at beginning
// numbers.shift();       // Remove first element

// console.log(numbers.length); // Array length

// 2.Advanced Array Operations
// let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
// let doubled = arr.map(num => num * 2);
// let even = arr.filter(num => num % 2 === 0);
// let sum = arr.reduce((acc, curr) => acc + curr, 0);

// console.log(doubled);
// console.log(even);
// console.log(sum);

// 3.Objects store data in key-value pairs.
// let student = {
//   name: "Rahul",
//   age: 21,
//   course: "MERN"
// };
// Object Operations
// console.log(student.name);
// student.city = "Hyderabad"; // Add property
// student.age = 22; // Update property
// delete student.course; // Delete property
// console.log(student);

// 4.Advanced Object Operations
// let keys = Object.keys(student);
// let values = Object.values(student);
// let entries = Object.entries(student);
// console.log(keys);
// console.log(values);
// console.log(entries);

// //Arrays help us store multiple values in an ordered way, while objects help store related data using key-value pairs. Advanced methods like map(), filter(), and reduce() make data processing easier and faster in JavaScript.

// 5. Processing Array of Objects

// An array of objects is commonly used to store structured data.

// let students = [
//   { name: "Amit", marks: 80 },
//   { name: "Riya", marks: 90 },
//   { name: "John", marks: 70 }
// ];
// Using map()
// let names = students.map(student => student.name);

// console.log(names);
// Using filter()
// let topper = students.filter(student => student.marks > 75);

// console.log(topper);
// Using reduce()
// let totalMarks = students.reduce((sum, student) => {
//   return sum + student.marks;
// }, 0);

// console.log(totalMarks);

// // Processing arrays of objects helps manage real-world data like students, products, or users. Methods such as map(), filter(), and reduce() are very useful for extracting, filtering, and calculating data efficiently.

// 5. Error Handling
// Error handling prevents the program from crashing.
// try-catch
// try {
//   let result = 10 / 0;
//   console.log(result);
// } catch (error) {
//   console.log("Error occurred");
// }
// Throwing Custom Error
// let age = 15;

// try {
//   if (age < 18) {
//     throw new Error("Not eligible");
//   }

//   console.log("Eligible");
// } catch (error) {
//   console.log(error.message);
// }
// finally Block
// try {
//   console.log("Try block");
// } catch (error) {
//   console.log(error);
// } finally {
//   console.log("Always executes");
// }

// // Error handling helps identify and manage runtime errors without stopping the program. Using try, catch, and finally improves application reliability and debugging.

// 4. Modules

// Modules help split code into separate reusable files.

// math.js
// export function add(a, b) {
//   return a + b;
// }
// app.js
// import { add } from "./math.js";

// console.log(add(2, 3));

// // Modules improve code organization by separating functionality into different files. This makes applications cleaner, reusable, and easier to maintain.

// 5. Named Export and Importing Named Export
// Exporting
// // utils.js

// export const name = "Rahul";

// export function greet() {
//   console.log("Hello");
// }
// Importing
// // app.js

// import { name, greet } from "./utils.js";

// console.log(name);

// greet();


// // Named exports allow exporting multiple variables or functions from one file. While importing, the exact exported names must be used inside curly braces.

// 6. Default Export and Importing Default Export
// Exporting Default
// // message.js

// export default function message() {
//   console.log("Welcome");
// }
// Importing Default
// // app.js

// import message from "./message.js";

// message();
// // A default export allows exporting only one main value from a file. During import, we can give any name to the imported function or variable without using curly braces.
